# Day 2 - OSI Layers

## Goal - Understand the OSI layers and their roles in networking.

## Layers:

--Physical Layer (Layer 1)
- Consists of physical components such as signaling, cables, and connectors.
- This layer does not contain many protocols.

# Physical Layer Problems:
- Caused by damaged cables, faulty fiber connections, or interference in wireless networks.

# Troubleshooting:
- Run a loopback test.
- Test or replace cables.
- Swap adapter cables or network cards.

--Data Link Layer (Layer 2)
- Provides the foundation for communication between devices on the same network.

-> Data Link Control (DLC)
- Often identified through the MAC (Media Access Control) address on Ethernet.
- It operates as a a switching layer and provides a unique hardware identifier for devices.

--Network Layer (Layer 3)
- Also known as the routing layer because routers use it to forward traffic.
- Uses Internet Protocol (IP) for addressing and routing.
- Data can be broken into fragments to travel across different networks.

# Troubleshooting:
- Problems related to IP configuration, subnet masks, and routing.

--Transport Layer (Layer 4)
- Responsible for transferring data from one device to another.
- Also called the host-to-host communication layer.
- Uses TCP (Transmission Control Protocol) and UDP (User Datagram Protocol).
- Breaks data into segments for transmission and reassembles them at the destination.

--Session Layer (Layer 5)
- Manages communication sessions between devices.
- Responsible for starting, maintaining, and ending connections.
- Includes control and tunneling protocols.

--Presentation Layer (Layer 6)
- Handles data formatting and character encoding.
- Manages application encryption and decryption.
- Often combined with the Application layer in many systems.

--Application Layer (Layer 7)
- The layer that users interact with through applications.
- Examples include HTTPS, FTP, DNS, and POP3.

# Learning Outcomes:
- Understood the role of each OSI layer.
- Learned common problems and troubleshooting techniques related to the seven layers of the OSI model.

# Real-World Example

When you open a website:

1. Application Layer – Your browser sends an HTTP/HTTPS request.
2. Presentation Layer – Data may be encrypted using SSL/TLS.
3. Session Layer – A session between your device and the server is established.
4. Transport Layer – TCP breaks the data into segments and ensures reliable delivery.
5. Network Layer – IP determines the route to the destination server.
6. Data Link Layer – Data is packaged into frames using MAC addresses.
7. Physical Layer – Bits travel through cables or wireless signals to reach the destination.
